{"title_page": "Semester at Sea", "text_new": "{{For|the album by [[Valley Lodge (band)]]|Semester at Sea (album)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Copy edit|for=capitalization, punctuation, [[WP:MOS]], and elimination of [[WP:PROMO]] nonsense|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Institute for Shipboard Education\n| former_names = {{Unbulleted list|University of the Seven Seas|World Campus Afloat}}\n| logo = [[File:Semester_at_Sea_Logo.jpeg]]\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| key_people = Dr. Gary A. Ransdell - CEO\n| industry = Study Abroad Program\n| founded = 1963\n| hq_location_city = Fort Collins, Colorado\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| website = https://www.semesteratsea.org\n}}\n[[Image:Semester at Sea Explorer 2005.jpg|thumb|350px|right|The {{MV|Explorer|2001|6}} docked in [[La Guaira, Venezuela]], a port sometimes visited by Semester at Sea]]\n\n'''Semester at Sea''' ('''SaS''') is a [[study abroad|study-abroad]] program that was founded in 1963. Managed by the Institute for Shipboard Education (ISE)<ref name=\"wilton\">{{cite web | last=Nash | first=James | title=Wiltonian spends 'Semester at Sea' | publisher=Wilton Villager | date=2010-01-07 | url=http://www.wiltonvillager.com/story/480305 | accessdate=2010-01-17 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718053012/http://www.wiltonvillager.com/story/480305 | archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]], USA, [[Colorado State University]] is the current academic sponsor <ref name=\"wilton\"/> while the program itself is run on a cruise ship. Throughout the history of the program, nearly 63,000 undergraduate students<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/contact/about-us/|title=About us|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=|df=}}</ref> from more than 1,500 colleges and universities have participated in Semester at Sea.\n\nDuring the spring and fall semesters, up to 600 undergraduates<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/life-at-sea/our-ship/|title=Our Ship|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Semester at Sea|accessdate=|df=}}</ref> participate in the approximately 100\u2013110-day program. During this semester, the ship circumnavigates the globe, travelling from [[North America]] and heading either east across the [[Atlantic]] or west across the [[Pacific]], visiting 10 to 11 countries in [[Asia]], [[Africa]], [[Europe]], [[South America]], and [[North America]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore Upcoming Voyages on the MV World Odyssey {{!}} Semester at Sea|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> Previously, the program had voyages that would sail through the Mediterranean and the Suez Canal, but due to piracy concerns in the [[Gulf of Aden]], voyages now typically travel around Africa.\n\nFor many years, ISE hosted a shorter 65-day Semester at Sea program in the summer that focused on one general region of the world. In May 2011, Semester at Sea introduced a new short-term or Maymester voyage with a curriculum based around the UN [[Millennium Development Goals]]. These voyages lasted 26 days and offered students the opportunity to earn four to five transferable credits. However, following the Maymester 2012 voyage, Semester at Sea decided to cancel short-term voyages indefinitely due to low enrolment. Additionally, a two-week ''\"Enrichment Voyage\"'' program was previously held for continuing education participants during December and January. Itineraries for these voyages focused on [[Central America]] and [[South America]], often transiting the [[Panama Canal]] or travelling up the [[Amazon River]]. Currently, ISE only offers fall and spring voyages.\n\n== Academics ==\nStudents attend classes on a variety of subjects and disciplines while the ship is at sea. Typically, these classes include [[humanities]] classes that are relevant to one or more of the countries on the itinerary. All students are also required to take an interdisciplinary core course, called [[Global studies|Global Studies.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/info-hub/academics/#semester-at-sea-course-information|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215223032/https://www.semesteratsea.org/info-hub/academics/#semester-at-sea-course-information|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-12-15|title=Course Information|format=PDF}}</ref> While in port, no classes are held and students can travel on Semester at Sea sponsored trips or independently in the country,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/our-program/in-country/|title=In-country destinations: field classes & program {{!}} Semester at Sea voyages|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> however, travel outside the country of a port is strictly prohibited, resulting in the student's dismissal from the program.\n\nAlthough [[Colorado State University]] is the academic sponsor for the program, Semester at Sea is open to students from any university. Faculty members are drawn from colleges and universities throughout the United States and around the world, including [[Harvard University]], [[Stanford University]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[Brown University]], [[Georgetown University]], [[George Washington University]], [[Boston University]], [[Bucknell University]], [[Emerson College]], [[Yale University]], [[University of Pittsburgh]], [[California Lutheran University]], [[Chapman University]], [[Bentley University]], [[Pennsylvania State University]], [[Duke University]], [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)]], [[Cornell University]], [[Jacksonville University]], [[University of Arizona]], [[University of Michigan]], [[National University of Singapore]], [[University of Virginia]], [[University of Colorado]], [[University of Maine]], [[University of San Diego]], [[University of Southern California]], [[University of Connecticut]], [[New York University]], and [[Columbia University]].\n\nBefore arriving at a port, students receive a pre-port briefing regarding the culture and societal rules of the country they are visiting. Upon arrival at the port of call, special guest speakers, ranging from community leaders from the country to American ambassadors, give lectures to the students and faculty. The pre-port briefing and the guest lectures are intended to help prepare students for their time in the country.\n\n== Notable lecturers and guests<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/our-program/experts/|title=Faculty & Staff - your expert education team {{!}} Semester at Sea voyages|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ==\n*[[Fidel Castro]], Cuban President\n*[[Anwar Sadat]], Egyptian President\n*[[Indira Gandhi]], Indian Prime Minister\n*[[Mikhail Gorbachev]], USSR President\n*[[Corazon Aquino]], President of the Philippines\n*[[King Mohammed VI of Morocco]], King of Morocco\n*[[Prince Moulay Rachid of Morocco]], Prince of Morocco\n*[[Archbishop Desmond Tutu]], Nobel Laureate\n*[[Mother Teresa]], Nobel Laureate\n*[[Nelson Mandela]], First Black President of South Africa, Nobel Laureate\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]], Author of 2001: A Space Odyssey\n*[[Pete Peterson]], First U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam\n*[[Tung Chee Hwa]], First Chief Executive of Hong Kong after end of British colonial rule\n*[[Paul Muldoon]], Irish poet\n*Prince [[Fahd Al-Saud]], Prince of Saudi Arabia\n\n== Ships ==<!-- https://www.semesteratsea.org/contact/about-us/ -->\n[[File:MS_Explorer.jpg|thumb|350px|right|MV ''Explorer'' departing [[Southampton]] June 2013.]]\n[[Image:S.S.UniverseExplorer-SemesterAtSea1997.png|thumb|350px|right|SS ''Universe Explorer'' docked in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], shortly before embarking on the Fall 1997 Semester at Sea voyage.]]\n\nIn May 2015, a lease was announced for the ship previously known as the {{MS|Deutschland|1998|6}}, to be renovated, re-flagged, and renamed the {{MV|World Odyssey|1998|6}},<ref>http://www.semesteratsea.org/our-ship/</ref> operated by [[V-Ships]].\n\nSemester at Sea has used a number of ships as its floating campus, including the MS ''Seven Seas'' (formerly the [[USS Long Island (CVE-1)|USS ''Long Island'']]), the SS ''Ryndam'', (not the later [[SS Rijndam|freighter]] of that name), the [[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS ''Universe'']], (formerly the [[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS Atlantic]]), the {{SS|Universe Explorer|1957|6}} and the {{MV|Explorer|2001|6}}. In 1972, one ship SaS intended to use, the [[S.S. Seawise University|SS ''Seawise University'']] (formerly the [[RMS Queen Elizabeth|RMS ''Queen Elizabeth'']]), burned, and subsequently sank, in [[Hong Kong Harbour]] during her conversion into a floating campus and consequently was never used for studies.<ref>{{cite web\n |title      = Media Kit\n |publisher  = Semester at Sea\n |url        = http://www.semesteratsea.org/index2.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=3&Itemid=838\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100617034841/http://www.semesteratsea.org/index2.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=3&Itemid=838\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2010-06-17\n |accessdate = 2008-08-21\n}}</ref> The ''Universe Explorer'', which retired in 2005, had a structure of four main decks with a small swimming pool in the stern of the ship. The ''Seawise University'', ''[[SS Atlantic (1953)|Universe]]'', and ''Universe Explorer'' were supplied and managed by [[Tung Chao Yung]]'s Seawise Foundation. Concerns regarding the separation of the Institute for Shipboard Education and the Seawise Foundation as well as the safety of the MV ''Explorer'' contributed to the [[University of Pittsburgh]] severing ties with the program in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Hart |author2=Mary Ann Thomas |title=Pitt to end pact with Semester at Sea program |url=http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-lay=a&-format=d.html&storyid=2629&-Find |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901091923/http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-lay=a&-format=d.html&storyid=2629&-Find |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 1, 2006 |work=University Times |location=[[University of Pittsburgh]] |date=June 9, 2005 |accessdate=May 19, 2009 |quote=...Pitt\u2019s concerns, charging that ISE left unanswered repeated requests by Pitt \u201cfor detailed assurances\u201d that the MV ''Explorer'' was seaworthy. Maher further maintained that ISE\u2019s decision to part ways with the Seawise Foundation, which for many years had supplied both SaS\u2019s previous ship, the S.S. Universe Explorer, as well as maritime management expertise, raised serious safety issues. }}</ref>\n\n== Ports of Call ==\nThe itinerary of destination ports is different each semester, typically docking at 10\u201311 ports around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore our Voyages|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, a spring itinerary included: [[Nassau, Bahamas]]; [[Caracas|Caracas, Venezuela]]; [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador, Brazil]]; [[Cape Town|Capetown, South Africa]]; [[Mombasa|Mombasa, Kenya]]; [[Chennai|Madras (Chennai), India]]; [[Singapore|Singapore, Penang (Malaysia)]]; [[Shanghai|Shanghai, China]]; [[Osaka|Osaka, Japan]]; and [[Hong Kong]].\n\nMore recent voyages have explored [[Hawaii]], [[Japan]], [[China]], [[Vietnam]], [[Myanmar|Myanmar (Burma)]], [[India]], [[Mauritius]], [[South Africa]], [[Ghana]], [[Morocco]], and the [[Netherlands]], with some variation. In Fall 2019, Semester at Sea embarked on a new voyage that included ports such as the Netherlands, [[Poland]], the [[Kiel Canal]] Transit, [[Portugal]], [[Spain]], [[Croatia]], Morocco, Ghana, [[Brazil]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Panama Canal]] Transit, [[Ecuador]], and [[Costa Rica]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore Upcoming Voyages on the MV World Odyssey|website=Semester At Sea|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n \nThe ship docked in [[Denmark]] during Summer 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Semester at Sea \u2013 Summer 2008 Itinerary/Calendar\n |url         = http://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/current-voyage/itinerary.php\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080703042836/http://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/current-voyage/itinerary.php\n |archivedate = 2008-07-03\n}}</ref> [[Namibia]] during Fall 2008, [[Bulgaria]] during Summer 2009, and [[Senegal]] during Fall 2015, the first time in the history of the program that Semester at Sea had visited these countries.\n\n== Traditions ==\n=== Neptune Day celebration ===\nWhen the ship crosses the equator, the students, faculty and crew of the vessel celebrate [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] Day, a maritime [[line-crossing ceremony]]. Students are transformed from \"[[pollywog]]s\" to \"shellbacks\" in an initiation ceremony, involving slime-smearing, fish-kissing, and (optional) [[head shaving|head-shaving]]. Neptune Day is one of several holidays celebrated during the voyage.\n\n=== Sea Olympics ===\nStudents aboard the ship are divided into groups named for various seas, (occasionally including [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]], [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]], [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]], [[Bering Sea|Bering]], [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]], [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], [[Red Sea|Red]], [[Yellow Sea|Yellow]], the [[Persian Gulf]], and the [[Three Seas Initiative|Three Seas]], (for the Lifelong Learners, faculty, and children of faculty). \n\nThe student seas are generally determined by their deck and will participate in an all-day Olympic challenge. Opening ceremonies are held in the morning, and no classes are held during the challenge. Events may include synchronized swimming, pull-ups, dodgeball, trivia, a lip-sync routine, and a ship-wide relay. The teams compete for the opportunity to disembark the ship first in its final port of call as well as a celebration in the faculty/staff-only lounge.\n\n==Notable Alumni==\n*[[Joan Lunden]], F67 \u2013 TV Host\n*[[Joel Douglas]], F67 \u2013 Film Producer \u2013 ''[[Romancing the Stone]]'' and ''[[The Jewel of the Nile]]''\n*[[Stephen Gaghan]], F86 \u2013 Emmy and Oscar Winning Screenwriter, ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]''\n*[[Cynthia Nixon]], S86 \u2013 Emmy Winning Actress \u2013 \"Miranda\" on TV show ''[[Sex and the City]]'' and challenged Andrew Cuomo<ref>[[Andrew Cuomo]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=October 2019}} in the 2018 New York Gubernatorial Election.\n*[[Richard Lamm]], S91 \u2013 Former Governor of [[Colorado]]\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]], F80, S83, S84, F84, F85 \u2013 Novelist, Wrote ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey]]''\n*[[Tory Burch]], S87 \u2013 Fashion Designer at [[Tory Burch LLC]]\n*[[David Milhous]], S87 \u2013 Emmy Winning Film and Television Editor, [[Crime Watch Daily]]\n*[[David Chokachi]], S89 \u2013 Actor on ''[[Baywatch]]''\n*[[Richard Threlkeld]], F94 \u2013 Journalist\n*[[Kristoffer Polaha]], F97 \u2013 Actor\n*[[Jonathan Murray]], S99 \u2013 Emmy Winning Producer, [[MTV]]'' [[Road Rules]]''\n*[[Kerri Strug]], F00 \u2013 Olympic Athlete\n*[[Robert Fulghum]], S01 \u2013 Author, ''[[All I Really Need to Know I Learned in Kindergarten]]''\n*[[Daphne Sheldrick]], S01 \u2013 Kenyan Naturalist, Expert on Elephants\n*[[Tyler Macniven]], S02 \u2013 [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Amazing Race]]'' 9 Winner\n*[[B.J. Averell]], S02 \u2013 [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Amazing Race]]'' 9 Winner\n*[[Aubrey O'Day]], F03 \u2013 Member of girl group [[Danity Kane]]\n*[[Iliza Shlesinger]], S04 \u2013 [[NBC]]'s ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'' Winner\n*[[Stuart Damon]], C05 \u2013 Emmy Winner, ''[[General Hospital]]''\n*[[Adam Braun]], S05 \u2013 Founder, [[Pencils of Promise]]\n*[[James King (English footballer)|James King]] \u2013 Professional Footballer\n*[[Jessica Flannery]] \u2013 Co-Founder, [[Kiva.org]]\n*[[Scott Seamans]] \u2013 Co-Founder, [[Crocs]]\n\n== Incidents ==\nThe Spring 1994 ([[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS ''Universe'']]) voyage ended in Hong Kong because the ship was scheduled for dry-dock maintenance after the voyage. However, the ship was unable to consistently meet its sailing schedule during the semester due to persistent mechanical difficulties. The ship made several unscheduled stops and had to anchor between ports while repairs were accomplished. It was decided to tow the ship to the [[South China Sea]] and anchor overnight. Captain Chang had all crew members patrolling the deck 3\u20135 feet apart with flashlights throughout the night to notify of any pirate boarding attempts. The planned stop at [[Manila|Manila, Philippines]] was canceled and the SS ''Universe'' rerouted to Singapore. Exams completed at anchor in the harbor, then the students and faculty flew to the next two planned ports of Osaka, Japan, and Shanghai, China. The ''Universe'' then met the students in Shanghai to complete the final leg of the voyage to Hong Kong.\n\nTraveling in foreign countries poses risks for all travellers and a few incidents of non-shipboard fatalities have occurred to participants of Semester at Sea. One student died in a hiking accident on a 1993 voyage, and SaS Spring 1996, five students were killed in a bus crash during a field trip in India.<ref>Hong, Peter (1996) \u201cDeaths Cloud Floating College : After Losing Children to Accidents, Parents Say Risks Weren't Publicized; Officials Defend Program\u201d,  http://articles.latimes.com/1996-06-17/local/me-15911_1_international-programs.  Accessed 2011-06-30</ref>\n\nThe Fall 1997 voyage was rerouted due to [[terrorism]] concerns. On November 12, 1997, [[Ramzi Yousef]] was convicted of masterminding the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]]. Consequently, the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] issued a travel warning for American citizens in the Middle East. On November 17, 1997, while the ship was docked in [[Port Said]], [[Egypt]], and the students were in [[Egypt]], the [[Luxor massacre]] occurred. Although no students were involved, fears of further terrorism resulted in the removal of the next two ports, [[Israel]] and [[Turkey]], from the itinerary, and the ship was rerouted to [[Cyprus]] and then [[Spain]].\n\nThe Fall 2000 semester on the SS ''Universe Explorer'' had two incidents. When entering Vietnam, the ship was hit by a barge, causing damage to the hull along the side of the ship and closing student rooms. No one was injured by this incident. The SS ''Universe Explorer'' had to remain an extra day in Vietnam to be patched but subsequently continued on the journey with all passengers. While preparing to head north through the Suez Canal to Egypt, Turkey, Croatia, and Spain, the ship's captain decided to reroute due to threats against all ships in the Suez region. Instead, the Fall 2000 voyage stopped in Kenya, South Africa, and Brazil.\n\nIn the Fall 2001 semester following the events of [[September 11 attacks|September 11]], the SS ''Universe Explorer'' was redirected after its stop in [[Kobe]], [[Japan]]. The planned route \u2014 from [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]], into the [[Indian Ocean]] through the [[Suez Canal]] to ports in [[Egypt]] and [[Croatia]] \u2014 was changed by the U.S. State Department. The ship's route for the semester was then rerouted south to include [[Singapore]], [[Seychelles]], and [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]. While in the Indian Ocean, the ship's communication with other vessels in the Indian Ocean was limited to protect the security of the American citizens on board.\n\nOn January 26, 2005, the MV ''Explorer'' weathered a combination of three storms in the [[North Pacific]], and a {{convert|50|ft|adj=on}} [[Rogue wave|freak wave]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Stories|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DBGhXI586k#t=8m42s|publisher=[[The Weather Channel]]|date=January 2005}}</ref> smashed the windows of the bridge, breaking one of them, and briefly affecting the navigation systems. The [[United States Coast Guard|US Coast Guard]] dispatched a [[Lockheed HC-130]] search and rescue plane (which shot footage of the vessel in the storm)<ref>{{cite web|title=CRUISE FROM HELL!!!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oUAUxxafZG4}}</ref> and two [[United States Coast Guard Cutter|cutters]] after receiving a distress call from the vessel.  There were no casualties, but two crew members were injured during the incident. Footage from February 14, 2005, was acquired from the sister ship, the [[Chinese Taishan|MV ''Grand Voyager'']] (now the Chinese Taishan) in Cyclone Valentina.<ref name=\"quchronicle\">{{cite web\n |title       = Semester at Sea ship narrowly averts disaster\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130104223047/http://www.quchronicle.com/2005/02/semester-at-sea-ship-narrowly-averts-disaster/\n |archivedate = 2013-01-04\n |url         = http://www.quchronicle.com/2005/02/semester-at-sea-ship-narrowly-averts-disaster/\n |accessdate  = 2008-03-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> \n\nWhile the vessel underwent repairs in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], Semester at Sea students were flown to [[Hong Kong]] to continue their courses. The MV ''Explorer'' rejoined the students in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]], and continued to circumnavigate the globe and complete the semester without further incident. The ordeal is documented in an episode of the [[The Weather Channel|Weather Channel]] television series ''[[Full Force Nature]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Stories|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DBGhXI586k|publisher=[[The Weather Channel]]|date=January 2005}}</ref> complete with home video taken by the students during the storm.<ref>{{cite web|last=Norville|first=Deborah|title=Semester at Sea|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ElQ4wsUqqi8|work=[[Inside Edition]]|authorlink=Deborah Norville|date=January 2005}}</ref> Later that year, safety concerns were among the reasons cited by the University of Pittsburgh for ending its 24-year academic sponsorship of the program.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.utimes.pitt.edu/?p=1396 | title=Provost explains decision to drop Semester at Sea | first=Peter | last=Hart | newspaper=University Times | publisher=University of Pittsburgh | location=Pittsburgh, PA | volume=37 | number=21 | date=2005-06-23 | accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Summer 2005 voyage was rerouted from [[London]] to [[Le Havre|Le Havre, France]], due to safety concerns after the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|London bombings]] on July 7, 2005.\n\nDuring the Fall 2006 voyage, [[Typhoon Shanshan (2006)|Typhoon Shanshan]] caused the MV ''Explorer'', en route from Japan to [[Qingdao, China]], to be rerouted to [[Hong Kong]].\n\nThe Summer 2008 voyage was rerouted from [[Istanbul|Istanbul, Turkey]], to [[Alexandria|Alexandria, Egypt]], due to bomb threats in Istanbul.\n\nDuring the Fall 2008 voyage, a University of Wisconsin student Kurt Leswing was hit and killed by a drunk driver in Hong Kong.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = Trial begins in drunken driving death of US student visiting Hong Kong\n  | work =\n  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/hkedition/2010-01/12/content_9303329.htm\n  | accessdate =2010-12-02}}</ref>\n\nFor the Spring and Fall 2009 voyages, the itinerary was altered to avoid the possibility of [[Piracy off the coast of Somalia|Somali pirates]] in the Gulf of Aden.\n\nDuring the Fall 2010 voyage, a [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] student Andre Ramadan died while docked in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], Vietnam.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = UCSB Student Dies While on Study Program\n  | work =\n  | url = http://dailynexus.com/2010-11-18/ucsb-student-dies-study-program/\n  | accessdate =2013-10-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring Spring 2011, the itinerary was changed following the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] that hit Japan. Instead, the MV ''Explorer'' docked in [[Taiwan]].\n\nIn Fall 2012, [[University of Virginia]] student Casey Schulman died from a recreational boating accident while docked in [[Roseau]], [[Dominica]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McCabe|first=Les|title=STATEMENT FROM PRESIDENT LES MCCABE ON DEATH OF FALL 2012 SEMESTER AT SEA PARTICIPANT|url=http://www.semesteratsea.org/2012/12/01/statement-from-president-les-mccabe-on-death-of-fall-2012-semester-at-sea-participant/|publisher=Semester at Sea|date=December 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Fall 2014 voyage was rerouted from Senegal and Ghana to Italy and Spain due to [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) and State Department warnings about the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola outbreak]] in Western Africa, and future voyages have been rescheduled as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Judge|first=Lauren|title=UPDATE FOR FALL 2014, SPRING 2015, AND FALL 2015 PARTICIPANTS REGARDING EBOLA OUTBREAK, ITINERARY CHANGES|url=http://www.semesteratsea.org/2014/08/04/update-for-fall-2014-and-spring-2015-participants-regarding-ebola-outbreak/|publisher=Semester at Sea|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Fall 2015 voyage on the MS ''World Odyssey'' was rerouted last minute from Turkey to Croatia to avoid possible terrorism and the [[European migrant crisis|refugee crisis]].\n\nThe Spring 2017 voyage was rerouted from Mauritius at the request of the vessel owner. The ship went directly from India to South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2017/03/11/important-message-regarding-spring-2017-itinerary/|title=Important Message Regarding Spring 2017 Itinerary|date=2017-03-11|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 2017, at approximately 1600 local time in [[Myanmar]], Kassandra (Kassie) Braun from St. Edward's University fell 20 feet from a [[pagoda]], sustaining fatal injuries. Braun was a 20-year-old student on independent travel in [[Bagan]] while participating in Semester at Sea's Fall 2017 Voyage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5062237/US-university-student-20-dies-fall-Myanmar.html|title=US university student, 20, dies after 30-foot fall in Myanmar|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/human-interest/20-year-old-indiana-college-student-falls-to-her-death-while-studying-abroad-in-myanmar/|title=Indiana College Student, 20, Falls to Her Death While Studying Abroad with Semester at Sea|date=2017-11-08|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2017/11/07/death-fall-2017-voyager/|title=Death of Fall 2017 Voyager|date=2017-11-07|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Spring 2020 voyage has avoided numerous countries, (including China), due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19)]]. The students on board the MV ''World Odyssey'' were rerouted to Vietnam where students received an extra week to make up for lost time in China. The MV ''World Odyssey'' left [[Kobe]], Japan, as scheduled on January 28, 2020, with arrival in [[Ho Chi Minh City|Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam]], on February 4, 2020. The ship was expected to have left [[Ho Chi Minh City]] at 0800 local time on February 16 but left 3 hours later at 1100 local time. The original itinerary had the MV ''World Odyssey'' stopping in Malaysia from February 19 to February 24 before heading to India from February 29 to March 5. Following a one-day fuel stop in Malaysia on February 19, the MV ''World Odyssey'' attempted to reroute to [[Victoria, Seychelles]] (with arrival expected on February 27 and departure on March 1). However, the evening before arrival, the Seychellois government denied the vessel entry. The MV ''World Odyssey'' then headed directly south to Mauritius and docked on February 29. The ship spent one day at port, followed by two days at sea around the island due to limited dock availability. The ship then returned to dock in [[Port Louis]] March 3\u20137. At about 0715 on March 6, students were informed of another itinerary change due to concerns of [[quarantine]] when arriving at European ports from northern Africa. On March 12, 2020, SaS canceled all South Africa programming, concluding the Spring 2020 voyage, and advised all students to return home when docked in Cape Town in light of the U.S. State Departments worldwide travel advisory.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2020/03/12/spring-2020-voyage-disembarkation-update-3-12-20/|title=Spring 2020 Voyage: Disembarkation Update (3-12-20)|last=|first=|date=March 12, 2020|website=Semester at Sea: News at the Helm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html?utm_campaign=Spring%202020%20Voyage%20Prep&utm_source=hs_email&utm_medium=email&utm_content=84632711&_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8FseLGLlH2Z4VjeJyztMJYfZyTcJv-q8Wtmj6YWsXVsGF7lf93UMVT7FzJnBmvU1K5VDXvl2Rg5KUvGf0TUjEF_TKiuw&_hsmi=84632711|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory \u2013 Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> All students were required to disembark from the MV ''World Odyssey'' by March 16, 1800 local time. Students were still required to continue their coursework remotely between March 17 and April 20.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Scholar Ship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.semesteratsea.org/}}\n* [http://www.thesmartset.com/article/article08060708.aspx The Smart Set: Is Responsible Travel Possible On Semester at Sea?]\n* [http://ships.galutschek.at/explorer/ Video Clip of Explorer leaving Halifax for the 2009 Summer Voyage]\n\n{{University of Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:Study abroad programs]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado]]\n[[Category:Chapman University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1963]]\n[[Category:Semester at sea programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the album by [[Valley Lodge (band)]]|Semester at Sea (album)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Copy edit|for=capitalization, punctuation, [[WP:MOS]], and elimination of [[WP:PROMO]] nonsense|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Institute for Shipboard Education\n| former_names = {{Unbulleted list|University of the Seven Seas|World Campus Afloat}}\n| logo = [[File:Semester_at_Sea_Logo.jpeg]]\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| key_people = Dr. Gary A. Ransdell - CEO\n| industry = Study Abroad Program\n| founded = 1963\n| hq_location_city = Fort Collins, Colorado\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| website = https://www.semesteratsea.org\n}}\n[[Image:Semester at Sea Explorer 2005.jpg|thumb|350px|right|The {{MV|Explorer|2001|6}} docked in [[La Guaira, Venezuela]], a port sometimes visited by Semester at Sea]]\n\n'''Semester at Sea''' ('''SaS''') is a [[study abroad|study-abroad]] program that was founded in 1963. Managed by the Institute for Shipboard Education (ISE)<ref name=\"wilton\">{{cite web | last=Nash | first=James | title=Wiltonian spends 'Semester at Sea' | publisher=Wilton Villager | date=2010-01-07 | url=http://www.wiltonvillager.com/story/480305 | accessdate=2010-01-17 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718053012/http://www.wiltonvillager.com/story/480305 | archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]], USA, [[Colorado State University]] is the current academic sponsor <ref name=\"wilton\"/> while the program itself is run on a cruise ship. Throughout the history of the program, nearly 63,000 undergraduate students<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/contact/about-us/|title=About us|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=|df=}}</ref> from more than 1,500 colleges and universities have participated in Semester at Sea.\n\nDuring the spring and fall semesters, up to 600 undergraduates<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/life-at-sea/our-ship/|title=Our Ship|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Semester at Sea|accessdate=|df=}}</ref> participate in the approximately 100\u2013110-day program. During this semester, the ship circumnavigates the globe, travelling from [[North America]] and heading either east across the [[Atlantic]] or west across the [[Pacific]], visiting 10 to 11 countries in [[Asia]], [[Africa]], [[Europe]], [[South America]], and [[North America]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore Upcoming Voyages on the MV World Odyssey {{!}} Semester at Sea|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> Previously, the program had voyages that would sail through the Mediterranean and the Suez Canal, but due to piracy concerns in the [[Gulf of Aden]], voyages now typically travel around Africa.\n\nFor many years, ISE hosted a shorter 65-day Semester at Sea program in the summer that focused on one general region of the world. In May 2011, Semester at Sea introduced a new short-term or Maymester voyage with a curriculum based around the UN [[Millennium Development Goals]]. These voyages lasted 26 days and offered students the opportunity to earn four to five transferable credits. However, following the Maymester 2012 voyage, Semester at Sea decided to cancel short-term voyages indefinitely due to low enrolment. Additionally, a two-week ''\"Enrichment Voyage\"'' program was previously held for continuing education participants during December and January. Itineraries for these voyages focused on [[Central America]] and [[South America]], often transiting the [[Panama Canal]] or travelling up the [[Amazon River]]. Currently, ISE only offers fall and spring voyages.\n\n== Academics ==\nStudents attend classes on a variety of subjects and disciplines while the ship is at sea. Typically, these classes include [[humanities]] classes that are relevant to one or more of the countries on the itinerary. All students are also required to take an interdisciplinary core course, called [[Global studies|Global Studies.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/info-hub/academics/#semester-at-sea-course-information|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215223032/https://www.semesteratsea.org/info-hub/academics/#semester-at-sea-course-information|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-12-15|title=Course Information|format=PDF}}</ref> While in port, no classes are held and students can travel on Semester at Sea sponsored trips or independently in the country,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/our-program/in-country/|title=In-country destinations: field classes & program {{!}} Semester at Sea voyages|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> however, travel outside the country of a port is strictly prohibited, resulting in the student's dismissal from the program.\n\nAlthough [[Colorado State University]] is the academic sponsor for the program, Semester at Sea is open to students from any university. Faculty members are drawn from colleges and universities throughout the United States and around the world, including [[Harvard University]], [[Stanford University]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[Brown University]], [[Georgetown University]], [[George Washington University]], [[Boston University]], [[Bucknell University]], [[Emerson College]], [[Yale University]], [[University of Pittsburgh]], [[California Lutheran University]], [[Chapman University]], [[Bentley University]], [[Pennsylvania State University]], [[Duke University]], [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)]], [[Cornell University]], [[Jacksonville University]], [[University of Arizona]], [[University of Michigan]], [[National University of Singapore]], [[University of Virginia]], [[University of Colorado]], [[University of Maine]], [[University of San Diego]], [[University of Southern California]], [[University of Connecticut]], [[New York University]], and [[Columbia University]].\n\nBefore arriving at a port, students receive a pre-port briefing regarding the culture and societal rules of the country they are visiting. Upon arrival at the port of call, special guest speakers, ranging from community leaders from the country to American ambassadors, give lectures to the students and faculty. The pre-port briefing and the guest lectures are intended to help prepare students for their time in the country.\n\n== Notable lecturers and guests<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/our-program/experts/|title=Faculty & Staff - your expert education team {{!}} Semester at Sea voyages|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref> ==\n*[[Fidel Castro]], Cuban President\n*[[Anwar Sadat]], Egyptian President\n*[[Indira Gandhi]], Indian Prime Minister\n*[[Mikhail Gorbachev]], USSR President\n*[[Corazon Aquino]], President of the Philippines\n*[[King Mohammed VI of Morocco]], King of Morocco\n*[[Prince Moulay Rachid of Morocco]], Prince of Morocco\n*[[Archbishop Desmond Tutu]], Nobel Laureate\n*[[Mother Teresa]], Nobel Laureate\n*[[Nelson Mandela]], First Black President of South Africa, Nobel Laureate\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]], Author of 2001: A Space Odyssey\n*[[Pete Peterson]], First U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam\n*[[Tung Chee Hwa]], First Chief Executive of Hong Kong after end of British colonial rule\n*[[Paul Muldoon]], Irish poet\n*Prince [[Fahd Al-Saud]], Prince of Saudi Arabia\n\n== Ships ==<!-- https://www.semesteratsea.org/contact/about-us/ -->\n[[File:MS_Explorer.jpg|thumb|350px|right|MV ''Explorer'' departing [[Southampton]] June 2013.]]\n[[Image:S.S.UniverseExplorer-SemesterAtSea1997.png|thumb|350px|right|SS ''Universe Explorer'' docked in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], shortly before embarking on the Fall 1997 Semester at Sea voyage.]]\n\nIn May 2015, a lease was announced for the ship previously known as the {{MS|Deutschland|1998|6}}, to be renovated, re-flagged, and renamed the {{MV|World Odyssey|1998|6}},<ref>http://www.semesteratsea.org/our-ship/</ref> operated by [[V-Ships]].\n\nSemester at Sea has used a number of ships as its floating campus, including the MS ''Seven Seas'' (formerly the [[USS Long Island (CVE-1)|USS ''Long Island'']]), the SS ''Ryndam'', (not the later [[SS Rijndam|freighter]] of that name), the [[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS ''Universe'']], (formerly the [[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS Atlantic]]), the {{SS|Universe Explorer|1957|6}} and the {{MV|Explorer|2001|6}}. In 1972, one ship SaS intended to use, the [[S.S. Seawise University|SS ''Seawise University'']] (formerly the [[RMS Queen Elizabeth|RMS ''Queen Elizabeth'']]), burned, and subsequently sank, in [[Hong Kong Harbour]] during her conversion into a floating campus and consequently was never used for studies.<ref>{{cite web\n |title      = Media Kit\n |publisher  = Semester at Sea\n |url        = http://www.semesteratsea.org/index2.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=3&Itemid=838\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100617034841/http://www.semesteratsea.org/index2.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=3&Itemid=838\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2010-06-17\n |accessdate = 2008-08-21\n}}</ref> The ''Universe Explorer'', which retired in 2005, had a structure of four main decks with a small swimming pool in the stern of the ship. The ''Seawise University'', ''[[SS Atlantic (1953)|Universe]]'', and ''Universe Explorer'' were supplied and managed by [[Tung Chao Yung]]'s Seawise Foundation. Concerns regarding the separation of the Institute for Shipboard Education and the Seawise Foundation as well as the safety of the MV ''Explorer'' contributed to the [[University of Pittsburgh]] severing ties with the program in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Hart |author2=Mary Ann Thomas |title=Pitt to end pact with Semester at Sea program |url=http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-lay=a&-format=d.html&storyid=2629&-Find |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901091923/http://mac10.umc.pitt.edu/u/FMPro?-db=ustory&-lay=a&-format=d.html&storyid=2629&-Find |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 1, 2006 |work=University Times |location=[[University of Pittsburgh]] |date=June 9, 2005 |accessdate=May 19, 2009 |quote=...Pitt\u2019s concerns, charging that ISE left unanswered repeated requests by Pitt \u201cfor detailed assurances\u201d that the MV ''Explorer'' was seaworthy. Maher further maintained that ISE\u2019s decision to part ways with the Seawise Foundation, which for many years had supplied both SaS\u2019s previous ship, the S.S. Universe Explorer, as well as maritime management expertise, raised serious safety issues. }}</ref>\n\n== Ports of Call ==\nThe itinerary of destination ports is different each semester, typically docking at 10\u201311 ports around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore our Voyages|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, a spring itinerary included: [[Nassau, Bahamas]]; [[Caracas|Caracas, Venezuela]]; [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador, Brazil]]; [[Cape Town|Capetown, South Africa]]; [[Mombasa|Mombasa, Kenya]]; [[Chennai|Madras (Chennai), India]]; [[Singapore|Singapore, Penang (Malaysia)]]; [[Shanghai|Shanghai, China]]; [[Osaka|Osaka, Japan]]; and [[Hong Kong]].\n\nMore recent voyages have explored [[Hawaii]], [[Japan]], [[China]], [[Vietnam]], [[Myanmar|Myanmar (Burma)]], [[India]], [[Mauritius]], [[South Africa]], [[Ghana]], [[Morocco]], and the [[Netherlands]], with some variation. In Fall 2019, Semester at Sea embarked on a new voyage that included ports such as the Netherlands, [[Poland]], the [[Kiel Canal]] Transit, [[Portugal]], [[Spain]], [[Croatia]], Morocco, Ghana, [[Brazil]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Panama Canal]] Transit, [[Ecuador]], and [[Costa Rica]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/|title=Explore Upcoming Voyages on the MV World Odyssey|website=Semester At Sea|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n \nThe ship docked in [[Denmark]] during Summer 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Semester at Sea \u2013 Summer 2008 Itinerary/Calendar\n |url         = http://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/current-voyage/itinerary.php\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080703042836/http://www.semesteratsea.org/voyages/current-voyage/itinerary.php\n |archivedate = 2008-07-03\n}}</ref> [[Namibia]] during Fall 2008, [[Bulgaria]] during Summer 2009, and [[Senegal]] during Fall 2015, the first time in the history of the program that Semester at Sea had visited these countries.\n\n== Traditions ==\n=== Neptune Day celebration ===\nWhen the ship crosses the equator, the students, faculty and crew of the vessel celebrate [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] Day, a maritime [[line-crossing ceremony]]. Students are transformed from \"[[Polywog|polywogs]]\" to \"shellbacks\" in an initiation ceremony, involving slime-smearing, fish-kissing, and (optional) [[head shaving|head-shaving]]. Neptune Day is one of several holidays celebrated during the voyage.\n\n=== Sea Olympics ===\nStudents aboard the ship are divided into groups named for various seas, (occasionally including [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]], [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]], [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]], [[Bering Sea|Bering]], [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]], [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]], [[Red Sea|Red]], [[Yellow Sea|Yellow]], the [[Persian Gulf]], and the [[Three Seas Initiative|Three Seas]], (for the Lifelong Learners, faculty, and children of faculty). \n\nThe student seas are generally determined by their deck and will participate in an all-day Olympic challenge. Opening ceremonies are held in the morning, and no classes are held during the challenge. Events may include synchronized swimming, pull-ups, dodgeball, trivia, a lip-sync routine, and a ship-wide relay. The teams compete for the opportunity to disembark the ship first in its final port of call as well as a celebration in the faculty/staff-only lounge.\n\n==Notable Alumni==\n*[[Joan Lunden]], F67 \u2013 TV Host\n*[[Joel Douglas]], F67 \u2013 Film Producer \u2013 ''[[Romancing the Stone]]'' and ''[[The Jewel of the Nile]]''\n*[[Stephen Gaghan]], F86 \u2013 Emmy and Oscar Winning Screenwriter, ''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]''\n*[[Cynthia Nixon]], S86 \u2013 Emmy Winning Actress \u2013 \"Miranda\" on TV show ''[[Sex and the City]]'' and challenged Andrew Cuomo<ref>[[Andrew Cuomo]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=October 2019}} in the 2018 New York Gubernatorial Election.\n*[[Richard Lamm]], S91 \u2013 Former Governor of [[Colorado]]\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]], F80, S83, S84, F84, F85 \u2013 Novelist, Wrote ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey]]''\n*[[Tory Burch]], S87 \u2013 Fashion Designer at [[Tory Burch LLC]]\n*[[David Milhous]], S87 \u2013 Emmy Winning Film and Television Editor, [[Crime Watch Daily]]\n*[[David Chokachi]], S89 \u2013 Actor on ''[[Baywatch]]''\n*[[Richard Threlkeld]], F94 \u2013 Journalist\n*[[Kristoffer Polaha]], F97 \u2013 Actor\n*[[Jonathan Murray]], S99 \u2013 Emmy Winning Producer, [[MTV]]'' [[Road Rules]]''\n*[[Kerri Strug]], F00 \u2013 Olympic Athlete\n*[[Robert Fulghum]], S01 \u2013 Author, ''[[All I Really Need to Know I Learned in Kindergarten]]''\n*[[Daphne Sheldrick]], S01 \u2013 Kenyan Naturalist, Expert on Elephants\n*[[Tyler Macniven]], S02 \u2013 [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Amazing Race]]'' 9 Winner\n*[[B.J. Averell]], S02 \u2013 [[CBS]]'s ''[[The Amazing Race]]'' 9 Winner\n*[[Aubrey O'Day]], F03 \u2013 Member of girl group [[Danity Kane]]\n*[[Iliza Shlesinger]], S04 \u2013 [[NBC]]'s ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'' Winner\n*[[Stuart Damon]], C05 \u2013 Emmy Winner, ''[[General Hospital]]''\n*[[Adam Braun]], S05 \u2013 Founder, [[Pencils of Promise]]\n*[[James King (English footballer)|James King]] \u2013 Professional Footballer\n*[[Jessica Flannery]] \u2013 Co-Founder, [[Kiva.org]]\n*[[Scott Seamans]] \u2013 Co-Founder, [[Crocs]]\n\n== Incidents ==\nThe Spring 1994 ([[SS Atlantic (1953)|SS ''Universe'']]) voyage ended in Hong Kong because the ship was scheduled for dry-dock maintenance after the voyage. However, the ship was unable to consistently meet its sailing schedule during the semester due to persistent mechanical difficulties. The ship made several unscheduled stops and had to anchor between ports while repairs were accomplished. It was decided to tow the ship to the [[South China Sea]] and anchor overnight. Captain Chang had all crew members patrolling the deck 3\u20135 feet apart with flashlights throughout the night to notify of any pirate boarding attempts. The planned stop at [[Manila|Manila, Philippines]] was canceled and the SS ''Universe'' rerouted to Singapore. Exams completed at anchor in the harbor, then the students and faculty flew to the next two planned ports of Osaka, Japan, and Shanghai, China. The ''Universe'' then met the students in Shanghai to complete the final leg of the voyage to Hong Kong.\n\nTraveling in foreign countries poses risks for all travellers and a few incidents of non-shipboard fatalities have occurred to participants of Semester at Sea. One student died in a hiking accident on a 1993 voyage, and SaS Spring 1996, five students were killed in a bus crash during a field trip in India.<ref>Hong, Peter (1996) \u201cDeaths Cloud Floating College : After Losing Children to Accidents, Parents Say Risks Weren't Publicized; Officials Defend Program\u201d,  http://articles.latimes.com/1996-06-17/local/me-15911_1_international-programs.  Accessed 2011-06-30</ref>\n\nThe Fall 1997 voyage was rerouted due to [[terrorism]] concerns. On November 12, 1997, [[Ramzi Yousef]] was convicted of masterminding the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]]. Consequently, the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] issued a travel warning for American citizens in the Middle East. On November 17, 1997, while the ship was docked in [[Port Said]], [[Egypt]], and the students were in [[Egypt]], the [[Luxor massacre]] occurred. Although no students were involved, fears of further terrorism resulted in the removal of the next two ports, [[Israel]] and [[Turkey]], from the itinerary, and the ship was rerouted to [[Cyprus]] and then [[Spain]].\n\nThe Fall 2000 semester on the SS ''Universe Explorer'' had two incidents. When entering Vietnam, the ship was hit by a barge, causing damage to the hull along the side of the ship and closing student rooms. No one was injured by this incident. The SS ''Universe Explorer'' had to remain an extra day in Vietnam to be patched but subsequently continued on the journey with all passengers. While preparing to head north through the Suez Canal to Egypt, Turkey, Croatia, and Spain, the ship's captain decided to reroute due to threats against all ships in the Suez region. Instead, the Fall 2000 voyage stopped in Kenya, South Africa, and Brazil.\n\nIn the Fall 2001 semester following the events of [[September 11 attacks|September 11]], the SS ''Universe Explorer'' was redirected after its stop in [[Kobe]], [[Japan]]. The planned route \u2014 from [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]], into the [[Indian Ocean]] through the [[Suez Canal]] to ports in [[Egypt]] and [[Croatia]] \u2014 was changed by the U.S. State Department. The ship's route for the semester was then rerouted south to include [[Singapore]], [[Seychelles]], and [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]. While in the Indian Ocean, the ship's communication with other vessels in the Indian Ocean was limited to protect the security of the American citizens on board.\n\nOn January 26, 2005, the MV ''Explorer'' weathered a combination of three storms in the [[North Pacific]], and a {{convert|50|ft|adj=on}} [[Rogue wave|freak wave]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Stories|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DBGhXI586k#t=8m42s|publisher=[[The Weather Channel]]|date=January 2005}}</ref> smashed the windows of the bridge, breaking one of them, and briefly affecting the navigation systems. The [[United States Coast Guard|US Coast Guard]] dispatched a [[Lockheed HC-130]] search and rescue plane (which shot footage of the vessel in the storm)<ref>{{cite web|title=CRUISE FROM HELL!!!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oUAUxxafZG4}}</ref> and two [[United States Coast Guard Cutter|cutters]] after receiving a distress call from the vessel.  There were no casualties, but two crew members were injured during the incident. Footage from February 14, 2005, was acquired from the sister ship, the [[Chinese Taishan|MV ''Grand Voyager'']] (now the Chinese Taishan) in Cyclone Valentina.<ref name=\"quchronicle\">{{cite web\n |title       = Semester at Sea ship narrowly averts disaster\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130104223047/http://www.quchronicle.com/2005/02/semester-at-sea-ship-narrowly-averts-disaster/\n |archivedate = 2013-01-04\n |url         = http://www.quchronicle.com/2005/02/semester-at-sea-ship-narrowly-averts-disaster/\n |accessdate  = 2008-03-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> \n\nWhile the vessel underwent repairs in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], Semester at Sea students were flown to [[Hong Kong]] to continue their courses. The MV ''Explorer'' rejoined the students in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]], and continued to circumnavigate the globe and complete the semester without further incident. The ordeal is documented in an episode of the [[The Weather Channel|Weather Channel]] television series ''[[Full Force Nature]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Storm Stories|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DBGhXI586k|publisher=[[The Weather Channel]]|date=January 2005}}</ref> complete with home video taken by the students during the storm.<ref>{{cite web|last=Norville|first=Deborah|title=Semester at Sea|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ElQ4wsUqqi8|work=[[Inside Edition]]|authorlink=Deborah Norville|date=January 2005}}</ref> Later that year, safety concerns were among the reasons cited by the University of Pittsburgh for ending its 24-year academic sponsorship of the program.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.utimes.pitt.edu/?p=1396 | title=Provost explains decision to drop Semester at Sea | first=Peter | last=Hart | newspaper=University Times | publisher=University of Pittsburgh | location=Pittsburgh, PA | volume=37 | number=21 | date=2005-06-23 | accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Summer 2005 voyage was rerouted from [[London]] to [[Le Havre|Le Havre, France]], due to safety concerns after the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|London bombings]] on July 7, 2005.\n\nDuring the Fall 2006 voyage, [[Typhoon Shanshan (2006)|Typhoon Shanshan]] caused the MV ''Explorer'', en route from Japan to [[Qingdao, China]], to be rerouted to [[Hong Kong]].\n\nThe Summer 2008 voyage was rerouted from [[Istanbul|Istanbul, Turkey]], to [[Alexandria|Alexandria, Egypt]], due to bomb threats in Istanbul.\n\nDuring the Fall 2008 voyage, a University of Wisconsin student Kurt Leswing was hit and killed by a drunk driver in Hong Kong.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = Trial begins in drunken driving death of US student visiting Hong Kong\n  | work =\n  | url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/hkedition/2010-01/12/content_9303329.htm\n  | accessdate =2010-12-02}}</ref>\n\nFor the Spring and Fall 2009 voyages, the itinerary was altered to avoid the possibility of [[Piracy off the coast of Somalia|Somali pirates]] in the Gulf of Aden.\n\nDuring the Fall 2010 voyage, a [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] student Andre Ramadan died while docked in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], Vietnam.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | title = UCSB Student Dies While on Study Program\n  | work =\n  | url = http://dailynexus.com/2010-11-18/ucsb-student-dies-study-program/\n  | accessdate =2013-10-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring Spring 2011, the itinerary was changed following the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] that hit Japan. Instead, the MV ''Explorer'' docked in [[Taiwan]].\n\nIn Fall 2012, [[University of Virginia]] student Casey Schulman died from a recreational boating accident while docked in [[Roseau]], [[Dominica]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McCabe|first=Les|title=STATEMENT FROM PRESIDENT LES MCCABE ON DEATH OF FALL 2012 SEMESTER AT SEA PARTICIPANT|url=http://www.semesteratsea.org/2012/12/01/statement-from-president-les-mccabe-on-death-of-fall-2012-semester-at-sea-participant/|publisher=Semester at Sea|date=December 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Fall 2014 voyage was rerouted from Senegal and Ghana to Italy and Spain due to [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) and State Department warnings about the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola outbreak]] in Western Africa, and future voyages have been rescheduled as well.<ref>{{cite web|last=Judge|first=Lauren|title=UPDATE FOR FALL 2014, SPRING 2015, AND FALL 2015 PARTICIPANTS REGARDING EBOLA OUTBREAK, ITINERARY CHANGES|url=http://www.semesteratsea.org/2014/08/04/update-for-fall-2014-and-spring-2015-participants-regarding-ebola-outbreak/|publisher=Semester at Sea|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Fall 2015 voyage on the MS ''World Odyssey'' was rerouted last minute from Turkey to Croatia to avoid possible terrorism and the [[European migrant crisis|refugee crisis]].\n\nThe Spring 2017 voyage was rerouted from Mauritius at the request of the vessel owner. The ship went directly from India to South Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2017/03/11/important-message-regarding-spring-2017-itinerary/|title=Important Message Regarding Spring 2017 Itinerary|date=2017-03-11|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 2017, at approximately 1600 local time in [[Myanmar]], Kassandra (Kassie) Braun from St. Edward's University fell 20 feet from a [[pagoda]], sustaining fatal injuries. Braun was a 20-year-old student on independent travel in [[Bagan]] while participating in Semester at Sea's Fall 2017 Voyage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5062237/US-university-student-20-dies-fall-Myanmar.html|title=US university student, 20, dies after 30-foot fall in Myanmar|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/human-interest/20-year-old-indiana-college-student-falls-to-her-death-while-studying-abroad-in-myanmar/|title=Indiana College Student, 20, Falls to Her Death While Studying Abroad with Semester at Sea|date=2017-11-08|work=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2017/11/07/death-fall-2017-voyager/|title=Death of Fall 2017 Voyager|date=2017-11-07|work=Semester At Sea|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Spring 2020 voyage has avoided numerous countries, (including China), due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19)]]. The students on board the MV ''World Odyssey'' were rerouted to Vietnam where students received an extra week to make up for lost time in China. The MV ''World Odyssey'' left [[Kobe]], Japan, as scheduled on January 28, 2020, with arrival in [[Ho Chi Minh City|Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam]], on February 4, 2020. The ship was expected to have left [[Ho Chi Minh City]] at 0800 local time on February 16 but left 3 hours later at 1100 local time. The original itinerary had the MV ''World Odyssey'' stopping in Malaysia from February 19 to February 24 before heading to India from February 29 to March 5. Following a one-day fuel stop in Malaysia on February 19, the MV ''World Odyssey'' attempted to reroute to [[Victoria, Seychelles]] (with arrival expected on February 27 and departure on March 1). However, the evening before arrival, the Seychellois government denied the vessel entry. The MV ''World Odyssey'' then headed directly south to Mauritius and docked on February 29. The ship spent one day at port, followed by two days at sea around the island due to limited dock availability. The ship then returned to dock in [[Port Louis]] March 3\u20137. At about 0715 on March 6, students were informed of another itinerary change due to concerns of [[quarantine]] when arriving at European ports from northern Africa. On March 12, 2020, SaS canceled all South Africa programming, concluding the Spring 2020 voyage, and advised all students to return home when docked in Cape Town in light of the U.S. State Departments worldwide travel advisory.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.semesteratsea.org/2020/03/12/spring-2020-voyage-disembarkation-update-3-12-20/|title=Spring 2020 Voyage: Disembarkation Update (3-12-20)|last=|first=|date=March 12, 2020|website=Semester at Sea: News at the Helm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html?utm_campaign=Spring%202020%20Voyage%20Prep&utm_source=hs_email&utm_medium=email&utm_content=84632711&_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8FseLGLlH2Z4VjeJyztMJYfZyTcJv-q8Wtmj6YWsXVsGF7lf93UMVT7FzJnBmvU1K5VDXvl2Rg5KUvGf0TUjEF_TKiuw&_hsmi=84632711|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory \u2013 Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> All students were required to disembark from the MV ''World Odyssey'' by March 16, 1800 local time. Students were still required to continue their coursework remotely between March 17 and April 20.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Scholar Ship]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.semesteratsea.org/}}\n* [http://www.thesmartset.com/article/article08060708.aspx The Smart Set: Is Responsible Travel Possible On Semester at Sea?]\n* [http://ships.galutschek.at/explorer/ Video Clip of Explorer leaving Halifax for the 2009 Summer Voyage]\n\n{{University of Virginia}}\n\n